<p><b>What are some questions for Lamb to the Slaughter?</b> </p>
<p><b>What grade level is Lamb to the Slaughter?</b> Middle School - 8th Grade ELA / Lamb to the Slaughter.</p>
<p><b>What is the message of Lamb to the Slaughter by Roald Dahl?</b> The main message is that appearances can be deceiving. Mary looks like a grieving housewife, but she is in fact a cold-blooded killer. The murder weapon appears to be some heavy tool but is in the fact the main ingredient in the dinner Mary prepared.</p>
<p><b>What is the main problem in Lamb to the Slaughter?</b> The conflict in 'Lamb to the Slaughter' is between Mary and her husband Patrick. When Patrick announces his intention to leave Mary and their unborn child, she resolves the conflict by killing Patrick with a frozen leg of lamb.</p>
<p><b>What is ironic about the questions in Lamb to the Slaughter?</b> Answer and Explanation: In this story, it is ironic that the leg of lamb itself is used to commit the slaughter (the murder of Mary's husband). Instead of being innocent, the lamb becomes associated with wrongdoing. As the murder weapon, this lamb is also the only evidence that can prove Mary committed the murder.</p>
<p><b>What does the lamb symbolize in Lamb to the Slaughter?</b> Lamb symbolizes both sacrifice and violence in “Lamb to the Slaughter.” It features in the story's title and in the leg of lamb Mary Maloney uses to kill her husband. The title evokes the idiom “like a lamb to the slaughter,” meaning an innocent person or creature who is oblivious to their impending fate.</p>
<p><b>How old is lamb when killed?</b> Lambs are sent to slaughter at the very young age of 10 weeks to one year – the average age of death is six to seven months, even though they could live up to 12 years old – that's just 1/24th of their natural life expectancy.</p>
<p><b>What does Patrick reveal to Mary?</b> Answer and Explanation: In Lamb to the Slaughter, Patrick tells Mary that he is leaving her, most likely because he has met another woman. Mary's first reaction is to not believe him.</p>
<p><b>Why does Mary insist that the officers eat dinner?</b> Mary Maloney forces the detectives to eat the leg of lamb because she wants to destroy the murder weapon. If she disposed of the leg in the trash, the men might wonder why she threw away a perfectly good leg of lamb.</p>
<p><b>What is the moral lesson of Lamb to the Slaughter?</b> 'Lamb to the Slaughter' teaches readers not to make assumptions about people. Patrick assumes that his wife will passively accept their divorce, and he dies because of it. He underestimates her anger and willingness to take action. The detectives make a similar mistake when they come to investigate the crime.</p>
<p><b>Why is the story called Lamb to the Slaughter?</b> Justify the title "Lamb to the Slaughter." That weapon once belonged to a real lamb that was "slaughtered" in order to be used as food. Patrick is the one who is "slaughtered" in the story. He is an easy victim of his enraged wife because, like a lamb going to the slaughter, he is completely unsuspecting.</p>
<p><b>How is Lamb to the Slaughter a metaphor?</b> Metaphorically, leading a lamb to slaughter means that a person is being led into a dangerous situation without being aware of what is happening, usually by trickery or deception. In Dahl's story 'Lamb to the Slaughter', this metaphor can be examined from three angles: Patrick leads Mary as the lamb to the slaughter.</p>
<p><b>What is the climax of lamb to slaughter?</b> The action of the story begins to rise as Mary waits for her husband to return in anticipation and continues to increase as it becomes clear that he is preparing to tell her something. It reaches its climax as he explains that he knows that it is a bad time and as he turns his back Mary hits him with the leg of lamb.</p>
<p><b>What are Mary's first thoughts after killing her husband?</b> Answer and Explanation: It occurred to her that perhaps he hadn't even spoken, that she herself had imagined the whole thing. '' After killing her husband, Mary becomes cold and calculating: ''It was extraordinary, now, how clear her mind became all of a sudden. She began thinking very fast.</p>
<p><b>Why was the husband killed in Lamb to the Slaughter?</b> Answer and Explanation: Mary kills Patrick because he is leaving her, even though she is six-months pregnant with their child.</p>
<p><b>What is the theme of Lamb to the Slaughter?</b> The theme of Roald Dahl's "Lamb to the Slaughter" revolves around betrayal and revenge. The main idea is the unexpected and ironic reaction of a wife to her husband's betrayal, leading to his murder. The purpose is to entertain while also highlighting the dark humor and unexpected twists in human behavior.</p>
<p><b>What is the moral dilemma of Lamb to the Slaughter?</b> Mary Maloney is both the protagonist and antagonist in "Lamb to the Slaughter," displaying moral ambiguity. Initially portrayed as a devoted wife, she murders her husband impulsively upon learning of his intent to leave her. She then cleverly conceals her crime, manipulating the police.</p>
<p><b>What does Mr. Maloney announce?</b> Maloney announces that he is abandoning her and wants a divorce. I would expect Mrs. Maloney to start weeping and begging him to stay with her since she loves and adores him so much. I also thought she would question him and explain his reasoning as to why he would want that.</p>
<p><b>What is the main conflict in the story Lamb to the Slaughter?</b> Conflict: The main conflict in Lamb To The Slaughter is character vs. self because Mary Maloney kills her husband because of the internal issues she was having because of the divorce, her emotions started to conflict and eventually she was over-come with a sense of rage.</p>
<p><b>What is the message of the Lamb?</b> The poem “The Lamb” reflects the teachings of the Bible by emphasizing God is a shepherd watching over his flock. Just like the speaker, is watching over the lamb. The poem “The Lamb” expresses Romantic theme of nature; as well as focusing on the motif of feeling a greater force within and a closeness to God.</p>
<p><b>What two things does the lamb symbolize?</b> In Christianity, the lamb represents Christ as both suffering and triumphant; it is typically a sacrificial animal, and may also symbolize gentleness, innocence, and purity. When depicted with the LION, the pair can mean a state of paradise.</p>
<p><b>What is the question in the poem the lamb?</b> Answer: In the poem “The Lamb”, the child speaker asks the lamb some naïve and yet profound questions like about its maker, source of food, delightful clothing and a pleasant voice. Though the questions are simply asked, they inquire about very grave knowledges like the origin and nature of creation.</p>
<p><b>What questions to ask about the lost sheep?</b> What does this story tell us about God's love for us? Why do you think Jesus told this parable? What does it mean to you today? Try retelling it in modern words.</p>
<p><b>What is the answer to the question of who made the lamb?</b> The speaker of the poem, possibly a shepherd, repeatedly asks the lamb “who made thee?” the answer is God, but the speaker is also saying God also made himself. The poem “The Lamb” reflects the teachings of the Bible by emphasizing God is a shepherd watching over his flock.</p>
<p><b>What is the answer to the question posed in the lamb?</b> Summary of "The Lamb" The child asks if the lamb knows about its own creation, its own being. In the second stanza, the child answers the question, saying that the lamb was created by God/Jesus Christ, with whom the lamb shares important characteristics, like being 'meek' and 'mild'.</p>